message.content:
We first identify the liquid assets (i.e. “quick assets”) as those current assets that can readily be turned into cash. In our case, the following end‐of‐period amounts are considered quick assets:
 • Cash on Hand: 2,882,590.91  
 • Bank Deposits: 2,698,390.00  
 • Interest Receivable: 9,066.78  
 • Accounts Receivable: 330,748.44  

Step 1. Sum the quick assets:  
 2,882,590.91 + 2,698,390.00 = 5,580,980.91  
 5,580,980.91 + 9,066.78 = 5,590,047.69  
 5,590,047.69 + 330,748.44 = 5,920,796.13  

Step 2. The total current liabilities at the end amount are given as 5,515,978.61.

Step 3. Calculate the Quick Ratio:  
 Quick Ratio = (Quick Assets) / (Current Liabilities)  
 = 5,920,796.13 / 5,515,978.61  
 ≈ 1.0734

Rounded to two decimal places, the Quick Ratio is approximately 1.07.

Thus, the solution in the required JSON format is:

{"solution": {'Quick Ratio': '1.07'}}
